'''Paul Chester Kainen''' is an American mathematician, an adjunct associate professor of mathematics and director of the Lab for Visual Mathematics at [[Georgetown University]].<ref>[http://math.georgetown.edu/faculty/ Mathematics faculty listing], Georgetown U., retrieved 2012-07-05.</ref> Kainen is the author of a popular book on the [[four color theorem]],{{sfnp|Saaty|Kainen|1977}} and is also known for his work on [[book embedding]]s of [[graph theory|graphs]].{{sfnp|Bernhart|Kainen|1979}}
==Biography== Kainen received his Bachelor of Arts degree from George Washington University in 1966 and was awarded the [[Ruggles Prize]] for Excellence in Mathematics. He went on to get his Ph.D. from Cornell University in 1970 with [[Peter Hilton]] as his thesis advisor.<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=9092}}</ref> Kainen's father was the American artist [[Jacob Kainen]].
==Selected publications== *{{citation | last1 = Saaty | first1 = Thomas L. | author1-link = Thomas L. Saaty | last2 = Kainen | first2 = Paul C. | location = New York | mr = 0480047 | page = ix+217 | publisher = McGraw-Hill International Book Co. | title = The four-color problem: Assaults and conquest | year = 1977}}. 2nd ed., Dover, 1986, {{ISBN|0-486-65092-8}}, {{MR|0863420}}. *{{citation|first1=Frank R.|last1=Bernhart|first2=Paul C.|last2=Kainen|title=The book thickness of a graph|journal=[[Journal of Combinatorial Theory]]|series=Series B|volume=27|issue=3|pages=320–331|year=1979|doi=10.1016/0095-8956(79)90021-2}}.
